  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 28-45.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - As in the former narrative section (vers. 4-24) David seems to have had his earlier troubles in mind, so, in the present one, his troubles since he entered upon the kingdom seem especially to engage his thoughts. These consisted chiefly of wars with foreign enemies, in which, while he incurred many dangers, he was, upon the whole, eminently successful. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 28.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For thou wilt light",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "my candle;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " rather, my ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "lamp",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " word generally used of the lamps supported by the seven-branched candelabrum of the tabernacle (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 25:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 37:22, 23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 40:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). David himself is called \"the lamp of Israel\" in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 21:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": ". The Lord my God will enlighten my darkness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The true lamp of David, which \"enlightened his darkness,\" was \"the light of God's countenance.\" While this shone upon him, his whole path was bright, and he himself, reflecting the Divine rays, was a lamp to others. Psalm 18:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(Heb.: 18:29-31) The confirmation of what has been asserted is continued by David's application of it to himself. Hitzig translates the futures in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". as imperfects; but the sequence of the tenses, which would bring this rendering with it, is in this instance interrupted, as it has been even in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", by כּי. The lamp, נר (contracted from nawer), is an image of life, which as it were burns on and on, including the idea of prosperity and high rank; in the form ניר (from niwr, nijr) it is the usual figurative word for the continuance of the house of David, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and frequently. David's life and dominion, as the covenant king, is the lamp which God's favour has lighted for the well-being of Israel, and His power will not allow this lamp (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 21:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to be quenched. The darkness which breaks in upon David and his house is always lighted up again by Jahve. For His strength is mighty in the weak; in, with, and by Him he can do all things. The fut. ארץ may be all the more surely derived from רצץ ( equals  ארץ), inasmuch as this verb has the changeable u in the future also in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 42:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ecclesiastes 12:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The text of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", however, certainly seems to put \"rushing upon\" in the stead of \"breaking down.\" With ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the first half of the hymn closes epiphonematically. האל is a nom. absol., like hatsuwr, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 32:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This old Mosaic utterance is re-echoed here, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 7:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the mouth of David. The article of האל points to God as being manifest in past history. His way is faultless and blameless. His word is צרוּפה, not slaggy ore, but purified solid gold, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 12:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Whoever retreats into Him, the God of the promise, is shielded from every danger. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 30:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is borrowed from this passage. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]